Ah, Novorossiysk. A city on the Black Sea, and frankly, a rather unremarkable one, if you ask me. It’s a port, you see. Ships come and go, carrying… well, whatever it is people deem important enough to transport across vast bodies of water. It was even designated a [Hero City](/Hero_City_(Soviet_Union)) by the Soviets. A title that feels as hollow as a drum now, doesn't it?

### History

The very shores of [Tsemes Bay](/Tsemes_Bay) have seen more action than the city itself. Back in antiquity, there was a Greek colony called Bata. They apparently specialized in the [grain trade](/Grain_trade). Imagine, peddling wheat. Strabo and Ptolemy bothered to mention it, which is more than can be said for most places.

After the Greeks, there were brief stints of [Roman](/Roman_Empire) and [Khazar](/Khazars) control. Then, from the 9th century, it became part of the [Byzantine](/Byzantine_Empire) empire, specifically the [Théma Khersonos](/Théma_Khersonos). This whole region seems to have been a revolving door for empires.

The 11th century brought the [Cumans](/Cumans), nomads from the steppe. Apparently, [Alexios I Komnenos](/Alexios_I_Komnenos), the Byzantine emperor, offered land to [Anglo-Saxon](/Anglo-Saxon) refugees fleeing the [Norman Conquest](/Norman_Conquest). They were to recapture the area from the nomads. There's some evidence of a [Byzantine-English colony](/New_England_(medieval)) being founded, with place names on the Kuban coast, like Susaco (or Susacho), possibly linked to [Sussex](/Sussex). There was even a river called Londina, no prizes for guessing its potential origin. It’s a bit of a stretch, but then again, so is most history.

By the 13th century, [Genoese](/Genoa) merchants, specifically the [Ghisolfi](/Ghisolfi) family, set up a trade outpost. Archeological digs in 2007 unearthed some interesting items, though I suspect they were more interested in the *items* than the *meaning*.

Later, the port became part of a chain of forts known as the Black Sea Coastal Line, stretching south to [Sochi](/Sochi). A rather precarious line of defense, I imagine.

The 19th century saw some development. It officially became a city in 1866 and the capital of the [Novorossiysk Okrug](/Novorossiysk_Okrug) and [Black Sea Governorate](/Black_Sea_Governorate) in 1896. It was the smallest part of the [Russian Empire](/Russian_Empire), which tells you something about the empire's priorities, or lack thereof. In 1905, it was the site of the short-lived [Novorossiysk Republic](/Novorossiysk_Republic). From 1918 to 1920, it served as the base for [Anton Denikin's](/Anton_Denikin) [White Army](/White_movement) during the [Russian Civil War](/Russian_Civil_War). Denikin's government fled to [Crimea](/Crimea), and many of his supporters escaped to [Constantinople](/Constantinople) with the help of [Allied](/Allies_(World_War_I)) warships during the [Evacuation of Novorossiysk (1920)](/Evacuation_of_Novorossiysk_(1920)). A rather ignominious exit, wouldn't you say?

During [World War II](/World_War_II), the Germans and Romanians occupied most of the city on September 10, 1942. A small group of Soviet sailors held out in a section called [Malaya Zemlya](/Malaya_Zemlya) for 225 days. They were eventually liberated by the [Red Army](/Red_Army) on September 16, 1943. The defense of the port, apparently, prevented the Axis from using it for supplies. Hence, the [Hero City](/Hero_City_(Soviet_Union)) title, awarded in 1973. A rather belated recognition for a rather desperate stand.

In 1960, [Dmitri Shostakovich](/Dmitri_Shostakovich) composed "Novorossiysk Chimes, the Flame of Eternal Glory" (Opus 111b). A musical tribute to… a port. How thrilling.

More recently, in 2003, [Vladimir Putin](/Vladimir_Putin) signed a decree for a naval base for the Black Sea Fleet. Billions were allocated for its construction. Russia even planned to move the entire fleet from [Sevastopol](/Sevastopol) to Novorossiysk by 2020. This whole saga with [Sevastopol](/Sevastopol) and [Ukraine](/Ukraine) is a rather tiresome affair, involving lease extensions and then, of course, the annexation of Crimea in 2014. It makes all the prior negotiations rather… moot.

### Administrative and Municipal Status

Novorossiysk is part of [Krasnodar Krai](/Krasnodar_Krai). It's designated as a [City](/City_of_federal_subject_significance), which means it’s an administrative unit with a status equivalent to that of the [districts](/Administrative_divisions_of_Krasnodar_Krai). Municipally, it's classified as Novorossiysk Urban Okrug. This administrative jargon is as exciting as watching paint dry.

### Coat of Arms

The coat of arms has a rather convoluted history. It was first approved in 1914 by Nicholas II. It featured a double-headed eagle, a crown, a scepter, and a power. On its chest, a scarlet shield with a golden Orthodox cross over a silver inverted crescent. In 1994, they ditched the Soviet version for a new one, and in 2006, they brought back the 1914 design with some modifications. The modern version has a gold shield, a black wavy tip, a black double-headed eagle crowned with an Imperial crown, scepter, and power. The wings bear a shield with a scarlet field, a golden eight-pointed cross atop a silver inverted crescent. And a golden five-pronged tower crown. It’s a lot. Frankly, it looks like something a child would draw after a particularly vivid fever dream.

### Geography

The city hugs the shore of [Tsemess Bay](/Tsemess_Bay) on the [Black Sea](/Black_Sea). It’s not exactly a *resort* town, unlike its neighbors [Anapa](/Anapa) and [Gelendzhik](/Gelendzhik). It does, however, oversee several urban settlements, the most notable being [Abrau-Dyurso](/Abrau-Dyurso). This place has a townlet on [Lake Abrau](/Lake_Abrau) and a village on the coast, connected by a rather winding mountain road.

The region around Novorossiysk is a significant [wine-growing](/Wineries) area. The [Abrau-Dyurso](/Abrau-Dyurso) wineries, established in 1870 by [Tsar Alexander III](/Tsar_Alexander_III), produce table and sparkling wines. I suppose that's something.

### Climate

Novorossiysk sits on the cusp of [humid subtropical](/Humid_subtropical) (Cfa) and [Mediterranean climate](/Mediterranean_climate) (Csa) zones. The driest month can have around 36 mm of [precipitation](/Precipitation), which can occur at any time of year, making a strict classification difficult. It’s neither here nor there, much like the city itself.

The climate data reveals average January temperatures around 2.9°C (37.2°F) and average July temperatures of 23.8°C (74.8°F). Record highs have reached a scorching 39.0°C (102.2°F), while the mercury has dipped to -18.0°C (-0.4°F) in January. It gets about 860.2 mm (33.87 inches) of rain annually, spread across roughly 70 days.

### Economy

The city's economy is largely tied to its port, the [Novorossiysk Commercial Sea Port](/Novorossiysk_Commercial_Sea_Port). It's the busiest oil port on the [Black Sea](/Black_Sea) and the endpoint for a pipeline from the [Tengiz Field](/Tengiz_Field) in [Kazakhstan](/Kazakhstan). It handles an impressive amount of cargo, with turnover figures often in the tens of millions of tons. It's also listed on the [Moscow Exchange](/Moscow_Exchange) and [London Stock Exchange](/London_Stock_Exchange).

Beyond the port, Novorossiysk is an industrial center. Think [steel](/Steel), [food processing](/Food_processing), and metal goods. The abundant [limestone](/Limestone) deposits fuel several [cement](/Cement) factories. For education, there's the Maritime State Academy and Novorossiysk Polytechnic Institute.

### Transportation

As Russia's largest seaport, Novorossiysk is a crucial transport hub. It's connected by rail and highways to major Russian cities, as well as [Transcaucasia](/Transcaucasia) and Central Asia. The [Novorossiysk railway station](/Novorossiysk_railway_station) serves as a key node.

The closest airports are [Gelendzhik Airport](/Gelendzhik_Airport), [Anapa Airport](/Anapa_Airport), and [Krasnodar Airport](/Krasnodar_Airport), located 33 km, 53 km, and 172 km away, respectively. They offer flights to numerous Russian cities.

### Sports

The local football team, [FC Chernomorets Novorossiysk](/FC_Chernomorets_Novorossiysk), competes in the Russian Second Division. Not exactly a global powerhouse, but it's something.

### Buildings and Structures

Notable structures include the [Novorossiysk TV Tower](/Novorossiysk_TV_Tower), the "Krasnaya Ploshchad" shopping mall, "Lenin's" Amusement Park, and the Malaya Zemlya Memorial. The memorial commemorates the tenacious defense during World War II.

### Notable Residents

The city has seen its share of notable individuals, though their significance varies. There's [Georges Gurvitch](/Georges_Gurvitch), a Russian-French sociologist and philosopher; [Seitumer Emin](/Seitumer_Emin), a Crimean Tatar writer and activist; and [Eugene Kaspersky](/Eugene_Kaspersky), founder of [Kaspersky Labs](/Kaspersky_Lab). There are also several football players and coaches, and a human rights defender, [Emir-Usein Kuku](/Emir-Usein_Kuku). Viktor Petrovich Skarzhinsky, a forester and landowner, also makes the list. It’s a rather eclectic mix, wouldn't you agree?

### Twin Towns and Sister Cities

Novorossiysk has a number of twin towns and sister cities. These include [Plymouth](/Plymouth) in the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) (though this relationship has been suspended since 2022), [Livorno](/Livorno) in [Italy](/Italy), [Valparaíso](/Valpara%C3%ADso) in [Chile](/Chile), [Gijón](/Gij%C3%B3n) in [Spain](/Spain), [Gainesville, Florida](/Gainesville,_Florida) in the [United States](/United_States), [Varna, Bulgaria](/Varna,_Bulgaria), [Pula](/Pula) in [Croatia](/Croatia), [Constanța](/Constan%C8%9Ba) in [Romania](/Romania), [Samsun](/Samsun) in [Turkey](/Turkey), [Tomsk](/Tomsk) in Russia, [Gavar](/Gavar) in [Armenia](/Armenia), [Novo Mesto](/Novo_Mesto) in [Slovenia](/Slovenia), and [Heilbronn, Germany](/Heilbronn,_Germany). It seems to be quite the international city, at least on paper.